<li class="commentbody" id="comment-613068">
			<cite>Limes</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-613068" title="">April 9, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">59</div>

				<p>I love, love, love French Onion Soup.  But I would not call it a cheap food to create.  The onions are cheap, yes.  But add up the costs of beef broth, Gruyère, vermouth, and a loaf of hearty bread?  It&#8217;s more like $20, not $5.</p>
<p>And when it comes to French cooking, it is the quality of the ingredients that make the difference. Sure, people could substitute, but the quality of this dish goes down substantially when that happens.</p>
<p>So I&#8217;d wholeheartedly agree with everything about this post, except that it is an economical dish to make.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
